Mock X-Ray Observations of Galaxy Clusters with Pisces & PyXSIM#

Overview#

In this walkthrough, weâ€™ll demonstrate how to generate mock X-ray observations of galaxy cluster models using PyXSIM alongside Pisces. This workflow allows you to create synthetic X-ray observations from astrophysical simulations, enabling direct comparisons with real X-ray telescope data.

By the end of this guide, youâ€™ll have a fully simulated X-ray dataset that can be used for further analysis or visualization.

Workflow Summary#

To generate realistic mock X-ray observations, we follow these four key steps:

  1. Defining the Cluster Profiles & Geometry

    • Set up the clusterâ€™s density, temperature, and velocity structure.

    • Define the spatial domain and physical parameters.

  2. Generating the Galaxy Cluster Model

    • Use Pisces to create a grid-based model of the cluster.

    • Populate the model with thermodynamic and kinematic fields.

  3. Converting the Model to a Particle Dataset

    • Convert the grid-based representation into a particle-based dataset.

    • This step allows us to use particle-based X-ray emission calculations in PyXSIM.

  4. Simulating X-Ray Emission with PyXSIM

    • Assign photon energies and emission properties to particles.

    • Generate a synthetic X-ray observation based on telescope parameters.

Getting Started#

Before we begin, ensure you have the required dependencies installed:

pip install pisces pyxsim yt astropy h5py

Now, letâ€™s dive into the first step: Defining the Cluster Profiles & Geometry. ðŸš€

Geometry and Profile Setup#

Since this model is spherical, setting up the geometry is straightforward. We can simply use the ``SphericalCoordinateSystem`` class from pisces.geometry.coordinate_systems. This ensures that all computations and spatial distributions naturally conform to a spherical coordinate system, without needing additional transformations.

To initialize the coordinate system, we do the following:

[2]:

# Import the spherical coordinate system class from pisces.
from pisces.geometry.coordinate_systems import SphericalCoordinateSystem

# initialize the coordinate system
coordinate_system = SphericalCoordinateSystem()

Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-03-02 18:22:58,348 Preparing Lame Coefficients for SphericalCoordinateSystem instance. This may take a few seconds...
Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-03-02 18:22:58,395 Preparing derived attributes for SphericalCoordinateSystem instance. This may take a few seconds...
Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-03-02 18:22:58,399 Lambdifying attributes...

Now that we have a coordinate system, the next task is to build the profiles for our galaxy clusters. We want two NFW Profiles of the correct general properties to be valid for a galaxy cluster. The NFW profiles in Pisces require a \(\rho_0\) and \(r_s\) parameter to be specified. Generally, \(r_s\) is on the order of 100â€™s of kpc in galaxy clusters. For such a system, the virial radius is \(\sim 4 r_s\) and so the virial mass is similar to

\[M_{\rm vir} \approx 1.4 \left[\frac{4}{3}\rho_0\pi r_s^3\right] \implies \rho_0 \approx \frac{3M_{\rm vir}}{4 \pi r_s^3}.\]

For a virial mass around \(10^{15}\,{\rm M}_{\odot},\) we need a \(\rho_0 \sim 1 \times 10^7 {\rm \frac{M_\odot}{kpc^3}}\).

For the density profile, weâ€™ll use a slightly steeper profile with only about 15% of the total mass.

[3]:

# Import the density profile class from the density
# module of the profiles library.
from pisces.profiles.density import NFWDensityProfile

# Create the halo and gas profiles.
total_profile = NFWDensityProfile(rho_0=1e7, r_s=200)
gas_profile = NFWDensityProfile(rho_0=1e6, r_s=150)

# Plot the profiles
x = np.geomspace(1e-1, 1e4, 1000)
total_density, gas_density = total_profile(x), gas_profile(x)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 1)

axes.loglog(x, total_density, color="darkblue", label=r"$\rho_{\rm tot}(r)$")
axes.loglog(x, gas_density, color="darkgreen", label=r"$\rho_{\rm g}(r)$")
axes.set_xlabel("Radii, [kpc]")
axes.set_ylabel(r"Density, $\left[{\rm M_\odot / kpc^3}\right]$")

Building the Model#

Now that the geometry is built and the density profiles are ready to go, the next step is to create the model.

To create the model in Pisces, we need to import ClusterModel from pisces.models.galaxy_clusters. We have the density and total density so we want to use from_dens_and_tden.

[4]:

# Import the model class.
from pisces.models.galaxy_clusters import ClusterModel

# Generate the model.
cluster_model = ClusterModel.from_dens_and_tden(
    "cluster_model.hdf5",  # The path to the model file.
    1e-1,  # Inner boundary (radius, kpc).
    1e4,  # Outer boundary (radius, kpc).
    gas_profile,  # Gas density profile.
    total_profile,  # total density profile.
    1000,  # Number of grid points.
    coordinate_system=coordinate_system,
    overwrite=True,
)

Generating Particles#

All Pisces models can be converted into particle datasets using a Virializer object. The Virializer does 3 things:

  1. Sample particles from the correct density field to create a set of particles.

  2. Interpolate fields onto the sampled particles.

  3. Determine the correct velocities for sampled particles (if they are collisionless).

Currently, virialization is not yet implemented.

Depending on the model youâ€™re working with, the Virializer might support some (or all) of these functionalities. For simulations, the relevant virializer needs to have all 3 functionalities; however, for many purposes, only the first 2 are relevant. They are also the easiest to implement. As an example, weâ€™ll convert our model into a particle dataset and them show how to export it to a yt dataset.

The first step is to import the correct virializer. For a spherical cluster, we can get the SphericalClusterVirializer from the pisces.models.galaxy_clusters module.

[5]:

from pisces.models.galaxy_clusters.virializers import SphericalClusterVirializer

# Initialize the virializer. The call takes the model (first arg) and the filename (second arg).
virializer = SphericalClusterVirializer(
    cluster_model, "cluster_particles.hdf5", overwrite=True
)

# Generate and interpolate
virializer.generate_particles({"gas": 4_000_000, "dark_matter": 1_000_000})
virializer.interpolate_fields()

# Fetch the reference to the particles.
particles = virializer.particles

Exporting Particle Data to YT#

The next task that needs to be performed is for the particles in Pisces to be converted to a yt particle dataset. To do so, weâ€™ll use the to_yt method. In order to create the ionization fields, weâ€™ll need to supply the default_species_fields kwarg (see here).

[6]:

pds = particles.to_yt(
    default_species_fields="ionized",
    length_units="kpc",
    bbox=[[-1.1e4, 1.1e4], [-1.1e4, 1.1e4], [-1.1e4, 1.1e4]],
)

Because yt doesnâ€™t yet treat our data as SPH data, we need to construct the correct SPH fields. yt provides a function to do this: .add_sph_fields!

We also need to create a temperature field. We only provided internal_energy (\(kT\)) when creating the original yt dataset so we need to add the temperature as a derived field. This can be done very quickly and efficiently.

[12]:

# Add the softening length field the the gas particles. This allows us to perform fluid computations
# with the particles.
pds.add_sph_fields(sph_ptype="gas")

[13]:

# Create the temperature field as well. (We have internal energy so we just need to scale)
from unyt.physical_constants import kb


def _temp(field, data):
    return data["gas", "internal_energy"] / kb


pds.add_field(
    name=("gas", "temperature"),
    function=_temp,
    sampling_type="local",
    units="K",
)

Creating Synthetic Observations#

Our next step is to model the X-ray emission from our system. We know the energy of each particle, so we need to produce a model of the emission dependent on the physics of the ICM. PyXSIM provides this for us:

[15]:

# Create the source model from the fully ionized source.
source_model = pyxsim.CIESourceModel("spex", 0.05, 11.0, 1000, 0.3, binscale="log")

[48]:

# Create the relevant xray fields.

xray_fields = source_model.make_source_fields(pds, 7.0, 25.0)
